# Fayetteville, North Carolina

## City in North Carolina, United States

### Fayetteville

Beneath a sky that has likely seen far too many human endeavors, lies [Fayetteville](/City), a principal [city](/City) firmly entrenched within the state of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), [United States](/United_States). Its central hub is, predictably, [Downtown Fayetteville](/Downtown_Fayetteville).

It presents itself with the expected civic adornments: a [Flag](/Flag), a [Seal](/Seal), and a [Logo](/Logo), all presumably designed to inspire some sense of local pride.

Its collection of informal titles, or "nicknames," offers a more candid glimpse into its self-perception and external reputation. These include the rather optimistic "America's Can Do City"—a phrase that seems to perpetually promise more than it delivers—and the equally earnest "All-American City." More evocatively, it's known as the "City of Dogwoods," a nod to its natural, fleeting beauty. Then there are the less flattering, yet perhaps more culturally resonant, appellations: "Fayettenam," a stark echo of a turbulent era, and "The Ville," a testament to the universal human tendency to abbreviate. Finally, "2-6" and "The Soldier City" unequivocally point to the dominant presence that defines much of its modern identity.

Its geographical placement is clearly delineated within [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) and the broader expanse of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), a detail that, while precise, hardly captures the full weight of its existence.

The city of [Fayetteville](/Fayetteville,_North_Carolina) can be precisely located on any map worth its salt, marked by the [coordinates](/Coordinates): 35°05′06″N 78°58′38″W. For those who prefer visual aids, it can be found on a [map of North Carolina](/Show_map_of_North_Carolina) and, for the truly ambitious, on a [map of the United States](/Show_map_of_the_United_States).

As a constituent part of the [United States](/United_States), it operates within the [State](/U.S._state) of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina) and serves as the very heart, the [county seat](/County_seat), of [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina). Its official founding, or "settlement," is recorded as 1783, a year that saw it christened in homage to a figure of some historical note: [Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette](/Gilbert_du_Motier,_Marquis_de_Lafayette).

Its governance structure adheres to the rather pragmatic [Council-Manager](/Council%E2%80%93manager_government) model. The current figurehead, the [Mayor](/Mayor_of_Fayetteville,_North_Carolina), is [Mitch Colvin](/Mitch_Colvin), representing the [Democratic Party (United States)](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), as of the most recent records. The day-to-day operational burden falls upon the [City Manager](/City_Manager), Douglas J. Hewett, a role that likely involves more thankless tasks than one could count.

In terms of sheer physical footprint, the city's [Area](/Area) encompasses a grand total of 150.08 square miles (388.71 square kilometers), though a significant portion of this is solid ground, with 148.26 square miles (383.99 square kilometers) designated as [land](/Land). The remaining 1.83 square miles (4.73 square kilometers) is, rather predictably, [water](/Water), accounting for a mere 1.21% of its total expanse—a detail that, if nothing else, confirms its terrestrial nature. Its average [elevation](/Elevation) hovers around 223 feet (68 meters), placing it at a modest height above sea level, far from the dramatic peaks or ocean depths that might actually command attention.

The city's [Population](/Population), as meticulously enumerated by the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census), reached 208,501 souls. A more recent [estimate](/Estimate) from 2023 nudges this figure slightly higher to 209,749, suggesting a slow, inexorable march of humanity. This places it at the [110th](/List_of_United_States_cities_by_population) position among cities in the [United States](/United_States) and the [6th](/List_of_municipalities_in_North_Carolina) most populous within [North Carolina](/North_Carolina) itself. The population [density](/Density) settles at a comfortable 1,406.3 individuals per square mile (542.99 per square kilometer). When considering its broader [Urban area](/Urban_area), the population swells to 325,008, positioning it as the [125th](/List_of_United_States_urban_areas) largest urban expanse in the U.S., with an urban density of 1,659 per square mile (640.5 per square kilometer). The encompassing [Metropolitan area](/Metropolitan_area), a sprawling network of interconnected lives, boasts an estimated 392,336 residents as of 2023, making it the [142nd](/Metropolitan_statistical_area) largest in the [United States](/United_States).

Living under the vast, indifferent sky, Fayetteville operates within the [Time zone](/Time_zone) of [UTC−5](/UTC%E2%88%925), specifically the [Eastern (EST)](/North_American_Eastern_Time_Zone). During the fleeting summer months, it shifts to [Daylight saving time](/Daylight_saving_time) (DST), observing [UTC−4](/UTC%E2%88%924) (EDT), a minor adjustment in the grand cosmic scheme.

Its postal identification, the [ZIP code](/ZIP_code), spans a rather extensive range: 28301, 28302, 28303, 28304, 28305, 28306, 28307 (specifically for [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg)), 28308 (for [Pope AAF](/Pope_Field)), 28309, 28310 (another designation for [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg)), 28311, 28312, and 28314. Communication is facilitated through [Area codes](/Telephone_numbering_plan) [910 and 472](/Area_codes_910_and_472), ensuring that its residents can, for better or worse, connect with the outside world. The [Federal Information Processing Standard](/Federal_Information_Processing_Standard) (FIPS) code is 37-22920, a bureaucratic identifier that, while useful, says little about the human experience within. Its [Geographic Names Information System](/Geographic_Names_Information_System) (GNIS) feature ID is 2403604, another data point in the relentless cataloging of existence.

For those requiring escape or ingress by air, the [Primary Airport](/Primary_Airport) is [Fayetteville Regional Airport](/Fayetteville_Regional_Airport). Within the city, [Public transportation](/Public_Transportation) is managed by the [Fayetteville Area System of Transit](/Fayetteville_Area_System_of_Transit), offering a means of traversing its streets for those without private conveyances. Further details, for the truly curious, can be found on its official [Website](/Website), www.ci.fayetteville.nc.us.

Fayetteville ([/ˈfeɪətvɪl/](/Help:IPA/English) *FAY-ət-vil*), though locally often pronounced [/ˈfɛdvəl/](/Help:IPA/English) *FED-vəl*, stands as a significant [city](/City) and the designated [county seat](/County_seat) of [Cumberland County, North Carolina](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina), within the [United States](/United_States). It’s notable for hosting [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg), a major [U.S. Army](/U.S._Army) installation, a fact that shapes much of its character, economy, and population.

The city has, on four separate occasions, been recognized with the rather self-congratulatory [All-America City Award](/All-America_City_Award) from the [National Civic League](/National_Civic_League). As of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census), its population tallied 208,501, securing its position as the [6th-most populous city in North Carolina](/List_of_municipalities_in_North_Carolina). Geographically, Fayetteville is situated within the [Sandhills](/Sandhills_(Carolina)) region, a distinct area in the western part of the [Coastal Plain](/Atlantic_Coastal_Plain), and is bisected by the venerable [Cape Fear River](/Cape_Fear_River).

With an estimated population swelling to 392,336 in 2023, the [Fayetteville metropolitan area](/Fayetteville,_North_Carolina_metropolitan_area) claims the title of the [second-](/North_Carolina_statistical_areas)[most populous](/Metropolitan_statistical_area) in southeastern [North Carolina](/North_Carolina) and ranks as the [142nd-most populous in the United States](/Metropolitan_statistical_area). The suburban sprawl that defines metro Fayetteville includes, but is not limited to, the military installations of [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) and [Pope Field](/Pope_Field), alongside the more conventionally named towns of [Hope Mills](/Hope_Mills,_North_Carolina), [Spring Lake](/Spring_Lake,_North_Carolina), [Raeford](/Raeford,_North_Carolina), [Rockfish](/Rockfish,_North_Carolina), [Stedman](/Stedman,_North_Carolina), and [Eastover](/Eastover,_North_Carolina). A truly comprehensive list of human habitation, for those who find such things fascinating.

## History

For a more granular, chronological descent into the past, one might consult the [Timeline of Fayetteville, North Carolina](/Timeline_of_Fayetteville,_North_Carolina). For the rest of us, a more general overview will suffice.

### Early settlement

The land that would eventually become present-day Fayetteville was not, as some might imagine, an empty canvas awaiting colonial inscription. It was, instead, the ancestral home of various [Siouan](/Siouan) [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) peoples. Among these were the [Eno](/Eno_people), the [Shakori](/Shakori), the [Waccamaw](/Waccamaw_Siouan), the Keyauwee, and the [Cape Fear](/Cape_Fear_Indians) people. These indigenous cultures had, with a remarkable persistence, followed a succession of other native groups in the area for a period exceeding 12,000 years, leaving their marks long before any European thought to plant a flag.

Following the rather unpleasant and violently disruptive periods of the [Yamasee War](/Yamasee_War) and the [Tuscarora Wars](/Tuscarora_War) during the second decade of the 18th century—conflicts that, like most human endeavors, were driven by a cocktail of greed and misunderstanding—the colonial government of [North Carolina](/Province_of_North_Carolina) saw fit to encourage further colonial settlement. Their gaze fell upon the upper reaches of the [Cape Fear River](/Cape_Fear_River), a waterway of some strategic importance, being the only navigable river entirely contained within the colony's borders. This led to the formation of two distinct, though perhaps not entirely harmonious, inland settlements: Campbelton and Cross Creek. Both were populated largely by [Scots](/Scottish_people), many of whom hailed from [Campbeltown](/Campbeltown) in [Argyll and Bute](/Argyll_and_Bute), [Scotland](/Scotland), bringing with them their distinct culture and, one presumes, a fair amount of stubbornness.

The merchants in [Wilmington](/Wilmington,_North_Carolina), ever practical and driven by the invisible hand of commerce, recognized the need for a town further up the [Cape Fear River](/Cape_Fear_River). Their aim, a perfectly understandable one, was to secure trade routes with the burgeoning frontier country. A genuine concern existed that goods might instead be diverted down the [Pee Dee River](/Pee_Dee_River) and find their way to the bustling port of [Charleston, South Carolina](/Charleston,_South_Carolina), bypassing Wilmington entirely. To mitigate this perceived threat, these shrewd merchants acquired land from a Newberry in Cross Creek. Meanwhile, Campbelton, in a rather less auspicious development, became known as a place where the less fortunate, both poor whites and free blacks, gravitated, earning it a reputation for a certain, shall we say, "lawlessness." A charming characteristic, to be sure.

In a move of civic expediency, 1783 saw the unification of these two disparate settlements, Cross Creek and Campbelton. The newly consolidated town was then formally incorporated as Fayetteville, a direct and rather transparent homage to [Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette](/Gilbert_du_Motier,_Marquis_de_Lafayette), the French military figure who had, with admirable strategic acumen, lent his considerable aid to the American forces during their war of independence. This act of naming holds a minor historical distinction: Fayetteville was, in fact, the very first city in the [United States](/United_States) to be named in the Marquis's honor. Lafayette himself, perhaps feeling a sense of obligation or merely enjoying a good parade, graced the city with his presence on March 4 and 5, 1825, during his rather extensive [grand tour of the United States](/Visit_of_the_Marquis_de_Lafayette_to_the_United_States).

### American Revolution

The local region, in the mid to late 1700s, experienced a significant influx of [Scots](/Scottish_people), predominantly [Gaelic](/Scottish_Gaelic)-speaking [Highlanders](/Scottish_Highlands). As is often the case with recent immigrants, the vast majority of these Highland Scots maintained a staunch loyalty to the British government, answering the call to arms from the Royal Governor with predictable fervor. This loyalty, however, proved to be somewhat misplaced, as they were ultimately outmaneuvered and defeated by a larger Revolutionary force at the decisive [Battle of Moore's Creek Bridge](/Battle_of_Moore%27s_Creek_Bridge). Despite this prevailing loyalist sentiment, the area also harbored a number of actively committed Revolutionaries, proving that human allegiances are rarely monolithic.

In a display of rather impressive foresight, or perhaps just a keen sense of impending doom, residents of the area drafted the "[Liberty Point Resolves](/Liberty_Point_Resolves)" in late June 1775. This document, a bold declaration of intent, predated the formal [Declaration of Independence](/United_States_Declaration_of_Independence) by just over a year, laying bare their grievances and aspirations. It contained the following, rather unequivocal, statement:

"This obligation to continue in full force until a reconciliation shall take place between Great Britain and America, upon constitutional principles, an event we most ardently desire; and we will hold all those persons inimical to the liberty of the colonies, who shall refuse to subscribe to this Association; and we will in all things follow the advice of our General Committee respecting the purposes aforesaid, the preservation of peace and good order, and the safety of individual and private property."

A rather wordy way of saying, "We're in this until it's fixed, and if you're not with us, you're against us." Robert Rowan, who appears to have been the unfortunate soul tasked with organizing this particular group, had the dubious honor of signing first, setting a precedent for leadership, or perhaps just for being the first to commit.

Robert Rowan (circa 1738–1798) was, by all accounts, one of the area's more prominent public figures of the 18th century. A man of many hats, he was a merchant and an entrepreneur, choosing to settle in Cross Creek sometime in the 1760s. His resume included stints as an officer in the [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War), a [sheriff](/Sheriff), a justice, and a legislator, eventually rising to become a leader of the Patriot cause during the [Revolutionary War](/American_Revolution). His legacy is etched into the local landscape: Rowan Street and Rowan Park in Fayetteville bear his name, as does a local chapter of the [Daughters of the American Revolution](/Daughters_of_the_American_Revolution). Curiously, [Rowan County](/Rowan_County,_North_Carolina), established earlier in 1753, was named not for him, but for his uncle, Matthew Rowan, a detail that must have caused some minor familial irritation.

[Flora MacDonald](/Flora_MacDonald) (1722–1790), a woman of considerable renown from the [Scottish Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands), known primarily for her daring aid to [Bonnie Prince Charlie](/Charles_Edward_Stuart) after the Highlander army's crushing defeat at [Culloden](/Battle_of_Culloden) in 1746, made her way to [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), residing there for approximately five years. Her loyalties, perhaps unsurprisingly, remained firmly with the British Crown, making her a staunch [Loyalist](/Loyalist_(American_Revolution)). She actively assisted her husband in rallying the local Scots to fight for the King against the encroaching tide of the Revolution, a testament to her enduring, if ultimately futile, convictions.

Even a local administrative division, Seventy-First Township in western [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) (now an integral part of Fayetteville), carries a direct historical link to this tumultuous period. It is named in honor of a British regiment that served during the American Revolution – the [71st Regiment of Foot](/71st_Regiment_of_Foot,_Fraser%27s_Highlanders), or as they were more romantically known at first, "Fraser's Highlanders."

The physical remnants of this era are still visible, if one cares to look. The center tile of the floor of the [Market House](/Market_House_(Fayetteville,_North_Carolina)) stands as a silent witness, having served as a town market until 1906. [Liberty Point](/Liberty_Point) in Fayetteville is another such site, where the aforementioned "Liberty Point Resolves" were signed in June 1775, a document that surely caused a few British officials to choke on their tea. The [Cool Spring Tavern](/Cool_Spring_Tavern), erected in 1788, holds the distinction of being the oldest surviving structure in Fayetteville, a sobering fact when one considers that most earlier buildings were unceremoniously obliterated by the "great fire" of 1831. A testament to either superior construction or sheer dumb luck, depending on your perspective.

### Post-revolution

The period immediately following the American Revolution is sometimes, with a touch of rose-tinted nostalgia, referred to as Fayetteville's "golden decade" during the 1780s. It was, for a brief shining moment, a focal point for the nascent state. In 1789, it hosted the state convention, a rather momentous occasion where the [U.S. Constitution](/U.S._Constitution) was finally ratified – a decision that shaped the future of the nation. Not long after, it also welcomed the [General Assembly](/North_Carolina_General_Assembly) session that saw the chartering of the [University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill](/University_of_North_Carolina_at_Chapel_Hill), an institution that would go on to shape countless minds. However, Fayetteville's aspirations to become the permanent state capital were ultimately dashed, losing out to the then-future city of [Raleigh](/Raleigh,_North_Carolina). A small setback, perhaps, but one that undoubtedly stung at the time.

In 1793, a local militia unit, the Fayetteville Independent Light Infantry, was formed. Rather remarkably, it remains active to this day (though one might question the precise definition of "active" for a ceremonial unit), holding the distinction of being the second-oldest [militia](/Militia) unit in the entire country. A testament to tradition, or perhaps just a reluctance to disband.

Henry Evans (circa 1760–1810), a free black preacher, is locally revered as the "Father of Methodism" in the area, a title that speaks volumes about his influence. Evans, a [shoemaker](/Shoemaker) by trade, was also a licensed [Methodist](/Methodist) preacher. Initially, he faced the predictable opposition from white residents when he began ministering to [enslaved people](/Slavery_in_the_United_States) in Fayetteville. However, his powerful sermons eventually transcended racial barriers, attracting white attendees to his services. He is credited with the significant achievement of constructing the town's first church, the African Meeting House, in 1796. The Evans Metropolitan [AME Zion Church](/AME_Zion_Church) proudly bears his name today, a lasting tribute to his enduring spiritual legacy.

On March 4–5, 1825, General Lafayette, the very namesake of the town, paid his celebrated visit. This was not just any stop; it was the first city named in his honor and, notably, the only one he personally visited during his extensive 1824-1825 tour of all the states as the "Nation's Guest." Admirers, undeterred by the rather inconvenient mud and pouring rain, lined the streets to welcome him. He was, as expected, fêted with a formal dinner, a grand ball, and numerous military displays—all the pomp and circumstance a grateful nation could muster, even if it meant getting a bit soggy.

### Antebellum

By 1820, Fayetteville's population had reached a respectable 3,500 residents. Despite this, [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) still ranked as only the second most urban county in the state, trailing behind [New Hanover County](/New_Hanover_County,_North_Carolina), home to [Wilmington](/Wilmington,_North_Carolina). However, the city's trajectory was dramatically altered by its "Great Fire" of 1831. This conflagration was, by contemporary accounts, considered one of the most devastating in the nation's history, a truly impressive feat of destruction, especially considering that, remarkably, no deaths were directly attributed to the incident. Hundreds of homes, businesses, and most of the town's most recognizable public buildings, including the venerable "State House," were reduced to ashes. In the aftermath, Fayetteville's leaders, with commendable, if grim, efficiency, moved swiftly to provide aid to the victims and commence the arduous task of rebuilding their devastated town.

There was, of course, no logical reason to reconstruct the old State House; the state government had long since firmly established itself in [Raleigh](/Raleigh,_North_Carolina). Instead, on the very site where the State House once stood, the city erected the iconic [Market House](/Market_House_(Fayetteville,_North_Carolina)). This new structure was designed to recreate the central hub that had previously surrounded the State House, effectively rebuilding the city around its enduring administrative and commercial heart. The Market House featured a practical covered area, a sensible design choice given that every single store in Fayetteville had been obliterated by the fire. Completed in 1832, it quickly became the primary administrative building for both the town and the county. It served as a bustling town market until 1906 and continued as Fayetteville's Town Hall until 1907. As of 2020, it has been repurposed, now serving as a local history museum—a fitting, if somewhat melancholic, testament to its long and varied past.

### The Civil War era through late 19th century

The grim specter of the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) cast its long shadow over Fayetteville. In March 1865, Gen. [William T. Sherman](/William_T._Sherman), with his formidable 60,000-man army, descended upon Fayetteville. Their mission, executed with ruthless efficiency, was to dismantle the [Confederate](/Confederate_States_of_America) [arsenal](/Arsenal), a structure of some architectural note, having been designed by the Scottish architect [William Bell](/William_Bell_(architect)). Sherman's troops, not content with merely destroying military infrastructure, also laid waste to foundries, cotton factories, and even the offices of [The Fayetteville Observer](/The_Fayetteville_Observer), ensuring a thorough disruption of the local economy and information flow. Not far from Fayetteville, the final [cavalry](/Cavalry) clash of the Civil War unfolded, a last, desperate struggle between Confederate and [Union](/Union_Army) troops at the [Battle of Monroe's Crossroads](/Battle_of_Monroe%27s_Crossroads).

Downtown Fayetteville itself was not spared the violence. On March 11, 1865, a skirmish erupted when Confederate Lt. Gen. [Wade Hampton](/Wade_Hampton_III) and his men, in a swift and unexpected maneuver, ambushed a Union cavalry patrol. The result was a stark reminder of the war's brutality: 11 Union soldiers killed and a dozen more captured.

Following the war, during the late nineteenth century, [North Carolina](/North_Carolina) unfortunately embraced the oppressive framework of [Jim Crow](/Jim_Crow) laws. These statutes systematically enforced [racial segregation](/Racial_segregation), ushering in an era of deep-seated discrimination and inequality that would scar the social fabric for generations. A rather predictable turn of events, given humanity's penchant for finding new ways to divide itself.

### 20th century to present

The mid-20th century brought a new surge of growth to [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina). In the 1960s, its population swelled by a remarkable 43%, marking the largest increase in any of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina)'s 100 counties. This demographic explosion naturally spurred a rapid pace of construction, with shopping developments and sprawling suburban subdivisions metastasizing beyond the existing Fayetteville city limits, extending inexorably towards the military behemoths of [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) and [Pope Air Force Base](/Pope_Air_Force_Base). The local school systems, those of Fayetteville and [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina), embarked on a gradual and often contentious path towards [integration](/Racial_integration), a process that began in the early 1960s and eventually saw wider-scale student integration in the 1970s, largely propelled by the controversial practice of [busing](/Desegregation_busing).

Despite these shifts, the segregation of public facilities clung on with stubborn resistance. The [Civil Rights Movement](/Civil_Rights_Movement) brought with it a wave of marches and sit-ins, with students from Fayetteville State Teachers College (now [Fayetteville State University](/Fayetteville_State_University)) standing at the vanguard of these protests. Their efforts ultimately chipped away at the entrenched discrimination, leading to the dismantling of "whites-only" service at restaurants and segregated seating in theaters. In a tangible reflection of these societal changes, both Black individuals and women began to secure public office in significant numbers from the late 1960s through the early 1980s, slowly but surely altering the political landscape.

The [Vietnam Era](/Vietnam_Era) proved to be a particularly transformative, and often traumatic, period for the Fayetteville area. Between 1966 and 1970, a staggering number of soldiers—over 200,000—underwent training at [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) before being deployed to Vietnam. This massive military buildup undeniably stimulated local businesses, creating a temporary economic boom. However, the war's shadow also brought dissent. [Anti-war protests](/Anti-war_protest) in Fayetteville garnered national attention, largely due to the city's close proximity to [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) and the fact that the city, for the most part, outwardly supported the conflict. Anti-war groups, ever seeking to amplify their message, notably invited the actress and activist [Jane Fonda](/Jane_Fonda) to Fayetteville to participate in three anti-war events, sparking considerable controversy. This era also coincided with a noticeable increase in crime and drug addiction, particularly along Hay Street, leading the media to coin the rather unflattering, yet undeniably memorable, nickname "Fayettenam." Furthermore, during this tumultuous time, Fayetteville found itself in the national headlines after Army doctor [Jeffrey R. MacDonald](/Jeffrey_R._MacDonald) brutally murdered his pregnant wife and two daughters in their [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) home in 1970. The book and subsequent film, [Fatal Vision](/Fatal_Vision), were based on these horrific events, cementing the city's association with a darker side of military life.

In a concerted effort to counteract the centrifugal forces of [suburbanization](/Suburbanization), Fayetteville has embarked on various [urban renewal](/Urban_renewal) initiatives, striving to revitalize its downtown core. These projects have, with varying degrees of success, managed to attract a number of large commercial and defense companies, including Purolator, [General Dynamics](/General_Dynamics), and [Wal-Mart](/Wal-Mart) Stores and Distribution Center. The development of significant regional attractions such as the [Airborne & Special Operations Museum](/Airborne_%26_Special_Operations_Museum), the Fayetteville Area Transportation Museum, Fayetteville Linear Park, and the Fayetteville Festival Park, which officially opened its gates in late 2006, has contributed to drawing visitors back to the city center.

The first decade of the 21st century witnessed considerable population growth in the towns and rural areas surrounding Fayetteville. Suburbs such as [Hope Mills](/Hope_Mills,_North_Carolina), [Raeford](/Raeford,_North_Carolina), and [Spring Lake](/Spring_Lake,_North_Carolina) experienced notable population increases, a clear indication of outward migration from the city's core.

A significant development occurred in 2005 when Congress enacted the [Base Realignment and Closure](/Base_Realignment_and_Closure) (BRAC) Act. This legislative action resulted in the relocation of several new commands to [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg), fundamentally altering the military landscape of the area. Among these were the [U.S. Army Forces Command](/U.S._Army_Forces_Command) (FORSCOM) and the [U.S. Army Reserve Command](/U.S._Army_Reserve_Command), both of which made the move from [Fort McPherson](/Fort_McPherson) in [Atlanta](/Atlanta). This massive relocation was projected to bring over 30,000 individuals to the area, along with their associated businesses and families, a demographic shift of considerable magnitude. FORSCOM alone, a veritable economic engine, awards over $300 billion in contracts annually, ensuring a steady flow of capital into the region.

In a rather unexpected accolade, the November/December 2009 issue of *Where to Retire* magazine singled out Fayetteville as one of the prime locations for military retirees in the [United States](/United_States). A testament to its amenities, or perhaps just a very effective marketing campaign.

However, not all news was entirely positive. In April 2019, a report compiled by GoBankingRates, which meticulously analyzed data from 175 American cities, cast a shadow of economic uncertainty. It listed Fayetteville as one of the top ten American cities facing a significant risk of a severe housing crash. The report highlighted that a concerning 26.8% of home mortgages in Fayetteville were "under water," while the median home value was a rather modest $108,000. These figures suggest a market teetering on the edge, a detail that might make one reconsider that retirement plan.

On a lighter, if somewhat peculiar, note, in December 2015, Fayetteville proudly unveiled what was officially recognized by the [Guinness World Record](/Guinness_World_Record) as the biggest Christmas stocking ever created. This colossal festive garment weighed approximately 1,600 pounds (730 kilograms) and measured a truly impressive 74.5 by 139 feet. One can only imagine the amount of coal required to fill it.

## Fort Bragg and Pope Army Airfield

The formidable presence of [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) and [Pope Army Airfield Field](/Pope_Army_Airfield_Field) anchors the northern sector of the [city of Fayetteville](/City_of_Fayetteville). These installations are not merely adjacent; they are inextricably linked to the city's identity and livelihood.

[Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) serves as the home base for a significant number of [U.S. Army](/U.S._Army) airborne units, a fact that contributes to the city's "Soldier City" moniker. Most prominently, it hosts the headquarters of the [XVIII Airborne Corps](/XVIII_Airborne_Corps_(United_States)), the renowned [82nd Airborne Division](/82nd_Airborne_Division), the [United States Army Special Operations Command](/United_States_Army_Special_Operations_Command), the [1st Special Forces Command (Airborne)](/1st_Special_Forces_Command_(Airborne)), and the prestigious United States Army [John F. Kennedy Special Warfare Center and School](/John_F._Kennedy_Special_Warfare_Center_and_School). A veritable who's who of elite military operations, all within easy reach.

At the genesis of [World War II](/World_War_II), [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) was the primary domain of the Field Artillery. A staggering 5,000 troops and all of the Army's [artillery](/Artillery) units east of the Mississippi River were based at this post. It was here that soldiers, with a mixture of skepticism and curiosity, put the Army's new bantam car—soon to be affectionately known as the [Jeep](/Willys_MB)—through its paces. A curious historical footnote, given that the primary source of power for moving artillery at the time still largely relied on the brute strength of horses and burros. On September 12, 1940, the Army formally contracted for a substantial expansion of the post, a move that facilitated the arrival of the [9th Infantry Division](/9th_Infantry_Division_(United_States)) to [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg).

The operational purpose of [Pope Field](/Pope_Field) is to provide essential [airlift](/Airlift) capabilities for American armed forces, extending its reach to humanitarian missions flown across the globe. Critically, [Pope Field](/Pope_Field) primarily handles air transportation for the [82nd Airborne](/82nd_Airborne_Division) and various other airborne units stationed at [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg), serving as their aerial gateway to deployment.

A notable shift in its operational profile occurred when all of Pope's [fighter jet](/Fighter_jet) squadrons were relocated to [Moody AFB](/Moody_AFB), Georgia. Consequently, the central entity at Pope is now the Air Force Reserve, though a small contingent of active personnel remains, dutifully carrying out their tasks.

In September 2008, Fayetteville, in a significant expansion of its municipal boundaries, [annexed](/Annexation) a substantial 85% of [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg)'s territory. This administrative maneuver instantly boosted the city's population to an impressive 206,000. Despite this annexation, [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg) judiciously retains its own independent police, fire, and EMS services, maintaining a degree of self-sufficiency. Fayetteville's strategic goal behind this expansion was clear: to leverage the newly incorporated population figures to attract larger retail businesses to the area, a rather transparent pursuit of economic gain.

## Sanctuary community for military families

In a move that could be seen as either genuinely benevolent or a shrewd public relations exercise, on September 5, 2008, [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) grandly proclaimed itself the "World's First Sanctuary for Soldiers and Their Families." To ensure this declaration was not merely hollow words, major roads within the county were adorned with distinctive blue and white "Sanctuary" signage, leaving little doubt about the county's new, self-appointed identity. The pledge was to furnish soldiers within the county with a comprehensive suite of local services, ranging from the practical provision of free childcare to the critical assistance of job placement for soldiers' spouses. A rather extensive list of offerings, if one considers the usual municipal duties.

To facilitate this ambitious undertaking, a small army of five hundred volunteers was enlisted, tasked with the rather significant responsibility of "watching over" military families. These volunteers were recruited to deliver personalized, one-to-one services, ensuring a human touch in their support. Furthermore, participating businesses, in a gesture of civic solidarity and perhaps a dash of enlightened self-interest, agreed to offer discounts and preferential treatment to military families. This initiative did not go unnoticed; *Time* magazine, in a moment of national recognition, lauded Fayetteville for its unwavering support of military families, identifying it as "America's Most Pro-Military Town." A title that, while perhaps a touch hyperbolic, certainly solidifies its reputation.

### 82D Airborne Division 4-mile Run

The presence of the [82nd Airborne Division](/82nd_Airborne_Division) is, of course, a defining characteristic of Fayetteville. One of their more visible traditions is the rigorous 4-mile run, a display of military fitness that regularly winds through parts of the city, serving as a constant, if somewhat exhausting, reminder of the dedicated personnel stationed within its borders.

## National Register of Historic Places

For those with a penchant for the past, or simply a desire to catalog every old building, further information on the various sites deemed worthy of preservation can be found in the comprehensive [National Register of Historic Places listings in Cumberland County, North Carolina](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina). A rather extensive compilation, for the truly dedicated.

## Geography

The city's territorial claims extend rather definitively to the west, reaching the [Hoke County](/Hoke_County,_North_Carolina) boundary. To its north, it abuts the town of [Spring Lake](/Spring_Lake,_North_Carolina), marking another limit in its inexorable expansion.

According to the always-precise, if somewhat dry, figures from the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), Fayetteville encompasses a total area of 150.08 square miles (388.7 square kilometers). Of this, a substantial 148.26 square miles (384.0 square kilometers) is solid [land](/Land), while the remaining 1.82 square miles (4.7 square kilometers), or a mere 1.21%, is, predictably, [water](/Water). A fact that, while accurate, hardly inspires awe.

### Topography

Fayetteville finds itself nestled within the [Sandhills](/Sandhills_(Carolina)) region of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), a distinct geographical zone that acts as a transitional buffer between the [coastal plain](/Atlantic_Coastal_Plain) to its southeast and the more elevated [Piedmont](/Piedmont_(United_States)) to its northwest. The city itself is quite literally built upon the banks of the [Cape Fear River](/Cape_Fear_River), a rather impressive 202-mile-long (325 km) waterway that begins its journey in [Haywood](/Haywood,_North_Carolina) and eventually, inevitably, empties into the vastness of the Atlantic Ocean. A testament to the relentless flow of nature, much like time itself. A short distance northeast of the city limits, on Carver Creek, a tributary of the [Cape Fear](/Cape_Fear_River), one can find Carver's Falls, a rather picturesque cascade measuring 150 feet (46 meters) wide and, quite literally, two stories tall. Additionally, [Cross Creek](/Cross_Creek_(Cape_Fear_River_tributary)) originates on the western side of Fayetteville, gracefully winding its way through to the eastern side of the city before merging with the [Cape Fear River](/Cape_Fear_River), a constant reminder of the interconnectedness of natural systems.

### Climate

Fayetteville exists within the rather predictable embrace of the [humid subtropical climate](/Humid_subtropical_climate) zone, classified by the [Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) as Cfa. This means, in essence, that it experiences mostly moderate temperatures throughout the year, a rather unremarkable, if comfortable, state of affairs. Winters are generally mild, though they can occasionally turn rather brisk, with the rare, fleeting occurrence of snow a few days per year—a minor inconvenience, at best. Summers, however, are a different beast entirely: hot, with oppressive levels of humidity that possess the rather inconvenient tendency to spontaneously generate thunderstorms and sudden, drenching rain showers.

The historical temperature records for Fayetteville span an impressive, if somewhat extreme, range: from a bone-chilling −5 °F (−21 °C) recorded on February 13, 1899, to a scorching 110 °F (43 °C) on August 21, 1983. This latter figure holds the rather dubious distinction of being the highest temperature ever officially documented in the entire [State of North Carolina](/North_Carolina), a testament to the sheer unpredictability of local weather. More recently, on [April 16, 2011](/Tornado_outbreak_of_April_14%E2%80%9316,_2011), Fayetteville was directly impacted by an EF3 tornado, a destructive event during what was [North Carolina](/North_Carolina)'s largest recorded tornado outbreak. Surrounding communities such as Sanford, Dunn, and [Raleigh](/Raleigh,_North_Carolina) also bore the brunt of this natural fury. The most recent and particularly noteworthy meteorological event to significantly affect Fayetteville was [Hurricane Helene](/Hurricane_Helene) on September 27th, which unleashed severe flooding across various parts of the city, a stark reminder that nature, much like fate, is often indifferent to human plans.

