### 2010 census

The [2010 census](/2010_United_States_census) recorded a population of 200,564 individuals, inhabiting 78,274 households, with 51,163 of these constituting traditional family units. The population density at this time was a rather efficient 1,401 inhabitants per square mile (541 per square kilometer). The housing landscape consisted of 87,005 units, averaging a density of 230.3 units per square kilometer (596.3 persons per square mile).

The racial composition of the city, as meticulously categorized, was: 45.7% [White](/White_(U.S._Census)), 41.9% [Black](/Black_(U.S._Census)) or [African American](/African_American), 2.6% [Asian American](/Asian_American), 1.1% [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States), a scant 0.4% [Native Hawaiian](/Native_Hawaiian) or [Other Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_American), 3.3% identifying as [some other race](/Race_(United_States_Census)), and a notable 4.9% identifying as [two or more races](/Multiracial_American). Furthermore, 10.1% of the total population identified as [Hispanic or Latino](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) of any race, illustrating the growing diversity of human faces within the city.

Delving into the household statistics, out of the 78,274 households, 36.7% harbored the relentless energy of children under the age of 18. A rather conventional 41.3% were headed by [married couples](/Marriage) cohabiting, while a not insignificant 19.5% were led by a female householder without a present husband, a testament to the myriad forms family takes. A full 34.6% were categorized as non-families, perhaps preferring the quiet solitude or the chaos of chosen companionship. Of all households, 28.7% consisted of individuals living alone, with 7.3% of these solitary figures being 65 years of age or older, perhaps contemplating the fleeting nature of companionship. The average household size was calculated at 2.45 individuals, with the average family size slightly larger at 3.02.

The city's population distribution by age was, as expected, a varied landscape: 25.8% were under the age of 18, 14.4% fell between 18 and 24, 28.5% were in the prime of 25 to 44, 21.5% ranged from 45 to 64, and 9.7% had reached the venerable age of 65 or older. The median age was a rather youthful 29.9 years, suggesting a vibrant, if sometimes naive, population. For every 100 females, there were 93.6 males, and among those aged 18 and over, the ratio shifted slightly to 90.5 males for every 100 females.

In 2013, the estimated median annual income for a household within the city was $44,924, while for a family, it rose slightly to $49,608. Male full-time workers earned a median income of $37,371, a figure that stood in contrast to the $32,208 earned by their female counterparts. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for the city was $23,362, a number that, like all averages, masks a multitude of individual financial realities. A rather stark 18.4% of the population and 16.2% of families found themselves living below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line), a sobering statistic. This included 27.1% of those under the age of 18 and 9.8% of those 65 and older, reminding us that vulnerability knows no age.

On September 30, 2005, Fayetteville, in a rather ambitious territorial grab, [annexed](/Annexation) a substantial 27 square miles (70 square kilometers) of land, along with its 46,000 residents. This action, predictably, was not without its challengers, as some affected residents and developers mounted legal challenges in the courts. Their efforts, however, proved largely futile, as they were ultimately unsuccessful. The notable exception was the Gates Four neighborhood, which, through sheer determination or perhaps a better legal team, managed to win its case against annexation, despite being entirely surrounded by newly incorporated areas. A small victory against the relentless march of municipal expansion.

## Religion

The spiritual landscape of Fayetteville is, predictably, as varied and complex as its human inhabitants.

Founded in Wade in 1758, [Old Bluff Presbyterian Church](/Old_Bluff_Presbyterian_Church) holds the distinction of being one of the most venerable churches in the Upper Cape Fear Valley, a testament to enduring faith, or perhaps just stubborn architecture. Annually, on the fourth Sunday of September, the church hosts the Old Bluff Reunion, an event that, with a commendable spirit of inclusivity, is open to the public. For those truly interested in the minutiae of its past, Bluff Presbyterian Church maintains a meticulously detailed history on its website.

Across [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) and its surrounding areas, hundreds of houses of worship have sprung up, catering to a diverse array of spiritual inclinations. These include, but are not limited to, [Catholic](/Catholic_Church), [Baptist](/Baptists), [Pentecostal](/Pentecostalism), [Methodist](/Methodism), and [Presbyterian](/Presbyterian) churches, with the latter two denominations boasting the largest congregations—a rather predictable outcome in this part of the world. Fayetteville also provides a home for Congregation Beth Israel, a community formed in 1910 by the [Jewish](/Judaism) families of Fayetteville, offering a distinct spiritual anchor.

St. Patrick Church in Fayetteville claims the title of the oldest [Catholic](/Catholic_Church) parish in the state, with its origins reportedly stretching back to the 18th century. A rather significant claim, though one might reasonably request an [independent source](/Wikipedia:Independent_sources) to corroborate such a venerable assertion.

The Masjid Omar ibn Sayyid mosque, a place of worship for the local [Muslim](/Muslims) community, bears a name of particular historical resonance. It is named after [Omar ibn Said](/Omar_ibn_Said), an African [Muslim](/Muslims) scholar who, in a rather cruel twist of fate, was jailed as a fugitive slave and subsequently sold in Fayetteville during the 19th century. Visitors to the [mosque](/Mosque) can, if they choose, delve into historical information about him and the resilient Muslim community that has taken root here. Furthermore, a historical marker dedicated to ibn Said was erected along Murchison Road in 2010, holding the distinction of being the first roadside marker in [North Carolina](/North_Carolina) to formally recognize a Muslim individual. A small, yet significant, step in acknowledging the complex tapestry of human history.

## Economy

The economic lifeblood of [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) flows primarily from one colossal entity: [Fort Bragg](/Fort_Bragg). This military installation, along with [Pope Field](/Pope_Field), injects an estimated $4.5 billion annually into the region's economy, a sum that rather definitively establishes Fayetteville as one of the country's most robust retail markets. Consequently, Fayetteville serves as the undisputed regional hub, a gravitational center for shops, restaurants, various services, lodging, comprehensive health care, and, naturally, entertainment. A rather straightforward economic ecosystem, driven by the steady hand of military expenditure.

As of March 2019, Fayetteville's unemployment rate stood at 5.2%. A figure that, while perhaps not catastrophic, was noticeably higher than both the national average of 3.8% and the [North Carolina](/North_Carolina) state average of 4%. A detail that, if nothing else, suggests a certain economic friction beneath the surface.

