### Defense industry

The Fayetteville area boasts a sizable and, by all accounts, continuously expanding [defense industry](/Defense_industry). This sector's prominence has not gone unnoticed by trade publications, which ranked the area among the top five in the [United States](/United_States) for defense-related activity in 2008, 2010, and 2011. A rather consistent performance, if one is keeping score. Eight of the ten largest American defense contractors have established a presence in the area, a testament to the magnetic pull of military spending. These corporate giants include such familiar names as [Lockheed Martin](/Lockheed_Martin), [Boeing](/Boeing), [Northrop Grumman](/Northrop_Grumman), [General Dynamics](/General_Dynamics), and [L-3 Communications](/L-3_Communications).

The city actively hosts the Partnership for Defense Initiatives (PDI), a trade association whose primary mission is to promote and support defense contractors. A rather clear indication of where the region's economic loyalties lie.

## Arts and culture

In a rather comprehensive October 2023 study released by [Americans for the Arts](/Americans_for_the_Arts) (AFTA), it was determined that nonprofit arts and culture organizations within Fayetteville and [Cumberland County](/Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) collectively generated a rather impressive $72.2 million in total economic activity throughout 2022. This cultural engine also supported over 1,100 jobs, provided $44.1 million in personal income to local residents, and contributed a significant $9.5 million in local, state, and federal tax revenue. A rather strong argument for the economic, if not purely aesthetic, value of the arts. Further underscoring this point, at an April 2024 event, the Arts Council of Fayetteville/Cumberland County proudly announced that arts and cultural activities had attracted more than 900,000 visitors to the region. A veritable flood of humanity, all drawn by the siren song of culture.

